<td><big><b><a href="/wiki/Portal:Politics" title="Portal:Politics">Portal:Politics</a></b></big></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The <b>paradox of hedonism</b>, also called the <b>pleasure paradox</b>, is the idea in the study of <a href="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">ethics</a> which points out that <a href="/wiki/Pleasure" title="Pleasure">pleasure</a> and <a href="/wiki/Happiness" title="Happiness">happiness</a> are strange phenomena that do not obey normal principles. First explicitly noted by the philosopher <a href="/wiki/Henry_Sidgwick" title="Henry Sidgwick">Henry Sidgwick</a> in <i>The Methods of Ethics</i>, the paradox of <a href="/wiki/Hedonism" title="Hedonism">hedonism</a> points out that pleasure cannot be acquired directly, it can only be acquired indirectly.</p>
